<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/8319F78A-DCBD-49F6-BE00-78E1CD75CDA9"><gtr:id>8319F78A-DCBD-49F6-BE00-78E1CD75CDA9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of York</gtr:name><gtr:department>Institute for Effective Education</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Heslington</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>York</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>North Yorkshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>YO10 5DD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Yorkshire and The Humber</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/8319F78A-DCBD-49F6-BE00-78E1CD75CDA9"><gtr:id>8319F78A-DCBD-49F6-BE00-78E1CD75CDA9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of York</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Heslington</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>York</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>North Yorkshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>YO10 5DD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Yorkshire and The Humber</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/C96EBB87-ED77-4594-8890-DCF7CA5C0928"><gtr:id>C96EBB87-ED77-4594-8890-DCF7CA5C0928</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Bette</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Chambers</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=ES%2FL00156X%2F1"><gtr:id>EF1FE0AA-9A78-42BD-994E-EC93A4C9EEB8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Different Perspectives on Overcoming the Challenges of Conducting Education Evaluations in Real-World Settings</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/L00156X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>In much of the western world there is a movement towards the use of evidence to inform education policy and practice (Campbell &amp;amp; Levin, 2012; Nutley, 2012; Slavin, 2012). Yet, this is not without its challenges. Some of these challenges come in the form of conducting large-scale Randomised Control Trial evaluations (RCTs) of education interventions in real school contexts with real teachers and real pupils. There are challenges for:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>policy makers and foundations in commissioning RCTs and other rigorous evaluations&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>researchers in recruiting the participants, conducting the studies and analysing the data&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>purveyors of the interventions in getting participants in the evaluation trained and supported&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>practitioners in implementing the interventions with fidelity&lt;/li>

&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>This seminar series brings together each of these stakeholders to debate the challenges and consider ways to overcome them. Each seminar provides a different perspective with international researchers, postgraduate students, policymakers, funders, programme developers and practitioners coming together to tackle the challenges in conducting quantitative evaluations of educational interventions and having the results of those evaluations influence policy and practice.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The theme of Year 1 is &lt;em>Challenges in Conducting RCTs in Real-World Settings&lt;/em> and&lt;em> &lt;/em>Year 2 is&lt;em> Analysing and Summarising Quantitative Data from Educational Studies&lt;/em>.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:potentialImpactText>The Institute for Effective Education (IEE), based at the University of York, has established links with UK educators and policy makers interested in evidence-based practice. It is important that this seminar series has an impact on as many stakeholder groups as possible. Our mission is to improve outcomes for all children, and in particular the most disadvantaged. In order to achieve this we not only need more, higher quality, quantitative evidence about what works; but also more policy makers promoting the use of evidence-based programmes; more organisations supporting and training schools in how to use programmes effectively; and more teachers feeling motivated, confident and supported in implementing what works in their classroom.

We therefore aim to ensure that this seminar series has an impact on the following stakeholder groups:
- Policy makers (local and national)
- School leaders and decision-makers
- Programme distributors
- Evaluation commissioners and funders
- Academic and research students

The ultimate beneficiaries will be schools, children, and society.

This seminar series encourages critical thinking and problem solving about the possibilities and difficulties of conducting high quality quantitative randomised evaluations in real-world settings, and analysing and interpreting the results of these, again to make a tangible difference. Policy makers, commissioners, and funders will benefit from this discussion by both developing a greater understanding of what constitutes high quality evidence and how to appropriately commission studies, as well as being able to contribute a view of what the policy world needs from evidence in order to be able to act upon it. 

School leaders and decision makers will gain a greater understanding of the essential role schools play in conducting research about what works and will also be able to share ideas about how to implement programmes with fidelity and help researchers understand the real-world situation schools operate in. Programme distributors will gain a greater understanding of the support that schools need and also what steps they can take to ensuring that their products are appropriately evaluated.

Academics, researchers, and research students will share expertise, skills, and methodological best practice in order to improve the quality of the research base and inspire further projects in this area. This will be of interest also to those working in a range of related disciplines such as health and social policy. In addition motivating and developing research students to have the desire and capacity to conduct high quality evaluations in education is a core part of the IEE's mission.

In the end, improving the debate and sharing expertise on the conduct and analysis of pragmatic evaluations in education will improve the quality of the research base about what works in education, ultimately impacting schools, improving attainment for children, and benefitting society as a whole.</gtr:potentialImpactText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2015-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2013-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>22912</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>How to Get What Works Working</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>EC951D41-160C-4CBD-841B-052367CD54EF</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Increased head-teachers awareness of presearch-proven literacy programmes

