sector>Education</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The overarching aim of the seminar series was to bring together various stakeholders in the area of evidence-based education to tackle some of the issues in conducting RCTs of educational interventions in real world settings and in analysing and summarising the quantitative data from educational research to inform educational policy and practice. This objective was realised.
Specifically, the objectives of the seminar series were to have leaders in the different domains of the education enterprise: researchers, policy makers, funders of educational evaluations, disseminators of educational interventions, education decision makers and practitioners share the challenges that they face in conducting evaluations and systematic reviews of evaluations so that collaboratively we could generate solutions to these issues. Through better understanding of the processes involved and the challenges that each stakeholder faces, came up with suggestions of ways of structuring RCTs and other large-scale evaluation to meet the needs of all participants.
Another objective was to disseminate the discussions and ideas generated widely to all stakeholders in the field with the aim of encouraging more systematic evaluations of educational interventions. With the growing bank of proven interventions, decision makers and practitioners can look to databases and websites of evidence-based interventions in deciding what interventions to implement with their pupils. This has been achieved by the submission of one journal article on the use of RCTs in education, mostly for researchers; the writing of another more generic article to a larger audience of policy makers, funders, and education administrators, and the publication of a special edition of Better:Evidence-based Education for teachers, head-teacher and other stakeholders in the education evaluation enterprise. The Better edition is a compilation of articles written in plain English by many of the presenters of the seminar series. 
The IEE has established links with UK educators and policy makers interested in evidence-based practice. This seminar series helped us expand our contacts to help the stakeholders in education evaluations engage in studies that are likely to improve outcomes for all children, and in particular the most disadvantaged. The seminar presentations highlighted the need for more higher quality, quantitative evidence about what works; to encourage policy makers to promote the use of evidence-based interventions; to have more organisations supporting and training schools in how to implement interventions effectively; and to have providers of interventions support teachers in implementing proven practices their classroom.
Academics, researchers, and research students shared expertise, skills, and methodological best practice to improve the quality of the research base and inspire further projects in this area. They learned to appreciate the challenges of schools in participating in evaluations. In addition, research students participated in the series and learned of the challenges on conducting high quality evaluations in education and ways of overcoming them.
In the end, improving the debate and sharing expertise on the conduct and analysis of pragmatic evaluations will improve the quality of the research base about what works in education, ultimately impacting schools, improving attainment for children, and benefitting society as a whole.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>This seminar series actively engaged following stakeholder groups:
? Policy makers (local and national)
